04_translate_point


  1. Question

    A wallpaper was made by using repeated translations. I have depicted the translation of point \((-0.2, 0.77)\) in the direction \(\theta=2.35\) (radians) by a distance of \(r=2.5\).


    What are the coordinates of the point at the end of the arrow (the result of the translation)?

    • The horizontal coordinate, \(x'=\)
    • The vertical coordinate, \(y'=\)


    Solution

    To find the changes of translation, we can use trigonometry.

    \[\Delta x = r\cdot \cos(\theta)\] \[\Delta y = r\cdot \sin(\theta)\]

    Let’s evaluate those changes.

    \[\Delta x ~=~ 2.5\cdot \cos(2.35) ~=~ -1.76\] \[\Delta y ~=~ 2.5\cdot \sin(2.35) ~=~ 1.78\]

    We can then add these changes to the original point.

    \[x' ~=~ x+\Delta x ~=~-0.2-1.76 ~=~ -1.96\] \[y' ~=~ y+\Delta y ~=~ 0.77+1.78 ~=~ 2.55\]

    Here is a picture with \(\Delta x\) and \(\Delta y\) depicted.
